<LP>
   A federal appeals court overturned a $5.2 million damages
award to entertainer Wayne Newton in his long-running libel
suit against General Electric Co.'s National Broadcasting Co.
unit.
   The suit is one of a growing number of cases in which
public figures sue on grounds that an article or broadcast
created a false impression, even if each statement taken
separately was true. In a ruling yesterday, the U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals in San Francisco found that most of the
factual statements in the broadcast were undisputed and that
any false impressions had not been shown to be deliberate or
reckless.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Supreme Court has ruled that public figures can't
win a libel case unless they prove that a statement was
false, defamatory and published with knowledge of its falsity
or with reckless disregard of whether it was true or false.
But Mr. Newton had alleged that he had been defamed by
implication and that the reporters must take responsibility
for the impressions they intentionally conveyed.
   The suit arose out of an Oct. 6, 1980, segment on NBC's
evening news titled "Wayne Newton and the Law." Mr. Newton
argued that the NBC report created the impression that he had
received financial assistance from organized-crime figures to
finance the purchase of a hotel. Among other things, he cited
the reporters' failure to include in the broadcast the fact
that he received a bank loan to finance the purchase.
   In December 1986, a jury in a Las Vegas, Nev., federal
district court found that the broadcast had created a false
impression and awarded Mr. Newton $19.2 million in damages.
Judge Myron Crocker, who heard the case, reduced the award to
$5.2 million, setting aside the jury's award for loss of
income and reducing an award for injury to reputation to
$50,000 from $5 million.
   "Wayne Newton's case poses the danger that First Amendment
values will be subverted by a local jury biased in favor of a
prominent local public figure against an alien speaker who
criticizes that local hero," the appeals court wrote.
   The appeals panel said that NBC could not be held liable
even if the broadcast created a false impression as Mr.
Newton alleged. The panel said the lower court improperly
considered its own view of the supposed false impression
instead of the intentions of the journalists who prepared the
broadcast. Such an approach, the panel wrote, "would permit
liability to be imposed not only for what was not said but
also for what was not intended to be said."
   The panel did not rule on whether the broadcast as a whole
was false. Instead, it based the ruling on the fact that Mr.
Newton had failed to show sufficient evidence that the
reporters deliberately lied or had been reckless with the
truth.
   Morton Galane, the Reno, Nev., lawyer who represented Mr.
Newton, said he could not comment because he was unable to
reach his client.
   "This is a case that never should have been brought or
gone to a jury in the first place. But the decision reaffirms
the willingness of the courts to afford protection in the
libel area when the jury system goes haywire," said Floyd
Abrams of the New York firm Cahill, Gordon &amp; Reindel, a
lawyer for NBC.
