   RACKETEERING CHARGES FILED against Asian fraternal
organization.
   A federal grand jury in Chicago indicted the On Leong
Chinese Merchants Association, and chapters of the nationwide
organization in three U.S. cities, on racketeering, gambling
and tax-fraud charges.
   The 34-count indictment -- which followed a 30-month
investigation -- alleges the operation of what prosecutors
call a "nationwide illegal gambling business." On Leong
chapters in Chicago, Houston, and New York were also accused
in the indictment of operating "casino-style" centers
featuring games of chance such as pai gow and fan-tan. Also
named as defendants were 29 officials and members of the
so-called tong, or association.
   Under racketeering law, prosecutors are seeking forfeiture
of certain On Leong properties, including the national
headquarters in New York, as well as about $11.5 million in
proceeds from the alleged gambling operation.
   On Leong officials couldn't immediately be reached for
comment.
   The indictment leans heavily on telephone conversations at
the Chicago chapter, which federal agents raided and closed
down in 1988.
   The indictment also cites conversations between the
defendants and Simon Au Yeung, an informant hired by the
Federal Bureau of Investigation to penetrate illegal Asian
organizations in the U.S. Mr. Au Yeung played a role in the
FBI's 1988 investigation.
   More recently he worked undercover to assist federal and
New York authorities in seizing 850 pounds of Southeast Asian
heroin allegedly imported by a different Chinese group.
